  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- Prohibit transactions designed to conceal the source of illegal funds\n- Require financial institutions to report suspicious activities\n- Establish reporting requirements for large cash transactions\n- Impose criminal penalties for money laundering offenses\n\n3. Specific Legal Frameworks:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 - Laundering of monetary instruments\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 - Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity\n\n4. Enforcement Agencies:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Department of Justice\n- Internal Revenue Service\n- Federal Bureau of Investigation\n\n5. International Cooperation:\n- Comply with Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Coordinate with international law enforcement agencies\n\nThese statutes provide comprehensive legal mechanisms to detect, prevent, and prosecute money laundering activities.",
